<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Again Kad- if the inspectors don't feel further inspections are practicable, then they will tell the UNSC and a second (termed) resolution would follow. Currently inspectors feel that results can be accrued (and the facts support this). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Understood, and agreed.  However, if the inspectors report that they no longer can accrue results, then their mission has failed.  But a strong dilemma exists within this lack of an exit strategy.  If they return with no results, the UN would be deemed to have failed.  This would be yet another crushing blow for the UN and it would further erode its relevancy in international and regional conflicts.  As everyone surely knows, and as was stated above, there are several hundred inspectors scouring a country the size of California.  I do not believe people understand the size and scope of the inspection job.  For me to drive from the middle of California where I live (Sacramento), to Los Angeles, it takes five hours.  That's just driving.  One can only guess the number of small cities between me and LA.  Now, can any one truly imagine inspecting every single facility between me and LA? And that is, maybe, one half the actual size!  Granted there are more people here than in Iraq (CA ~35 Million people and Iraq = ~24 million).  My point is, with a force of several hundred in the field, the size of the job really is nearly infinite.<br>
<br>
Therefore, the inspectors will always feel the potential to accrue more results merely based on the size of the job.  (For clarity purposes, I have not including extra-circumstances that add to the difficulty of inpections such as hidden bunkers, roaming mobile facilities, weapons stored in homes, etc.)<br>
<br>
Respectfully,<br>
Kad<br>
<br>
Cliff Notes Version:  The weapons inspectors, facing extreme pressure from the UN to not fail because doing so will result in a serious hit on UN relevance, will never ask the UNSC for a 2nd resolution because the size of their job is nearly infinite.  The inspectors will always feel there is more to inspect (based merely on the size of Iraq) and therefore they believe inspections should continue.  They lack a viable exit strategy. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kwaij>kwaij</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Baby clubber!!</span><br>  Posts: 396<br> <font color=#333333>(3/13/03 12:24 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Moordred</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Saddam Hussein recently authorized Iraqi field commanders to use chemical weapons, the very weapons the dictator tells the world he does not have,&quot; Bush said<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
