<br>
Rubbish.  If inspectors can't accrue results it'll be because they feel that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Saddam</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is not complying sufficiently for inspections to continue.  I doubt anyone in the international community would be so idiotic as to blame the UN for a lack of compliance from the Iraqi side severe enough to warrant the closure of inspections.  <br>
<br>
Rather, the UN will be seriously damaged if permanent members decide not to seek a resolution explicitly authorising force.  Unless the United States and Britain (+allies) can convince 9 members of the UNSC including themselves of the validity of military action absenting vetoes, then it is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>they</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> who will undermine the UN's authority by seeking to act outside its auspices.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As everyone surely knows, and as was stated above, there are several hundred inspectors scouring a country the size of California. I do not believe people understand the size and scope of the inspection job.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Which is why inspections are intelligence-driven.  Using that analogy, it would be theoretically impossible to disarm <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>any</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> country larger than Liechtenstein.  With ELINT combing Iraq in numerous forms, and hard HUMINT (from MI-6/SIS, CIA, Mossad et al) coming in on a daily basis feeding inspectors with the information they need, I see no reason why inspections here don't work as effectively as they did in, say, the Ukraine- a larger country.  Although, as you rightly point out, applying intelligence to a large number of targets does take time- those who I've spoken to in the intelligence field assure me that simply analyzing the plausibility(never mind the veracity) of information can take days, sometimes weeks depending on the source.  Thus, the Bush and Blair administrations' collective impatience on the matter is wholly unreasonable given the practical difficulties of data that need to be overcome.<br>
<br>
The other compelling argument that's often overlooked is track record &amp; field position.  UN inspection teams have a nearly flawless track record in disarming nation states, numerous inspections have taken place in a satisfactory manner, taking anywhere from months (South Africa) to 6 years (Ukraine/Tajikistan).  Fact is, no single nation state even approaches the success rate or experience level of UN inspection teams in this regard.  Therefore I am extremely skeptical of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>any</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> government's position regarding the success of inspections- they are the best judge, and none of us are listening to them, the experts on the ground enough.  I certainly do acknowledge however, that the Franco-Russian position represents the accuracy of inspection success far more accurately and honestly than the Anglo-American position.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I referenced (as much as I despise doing so) the intent portion of the resolution merely to bring to light of the fact that the world, through its UN representatives and their unanimous approval, has declared Iraq a threat to world peace<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Declaring Iraq a threat to world peace is a statement of a theoretical threat, not an imminent one.  Note that nowhere in the resolution (OCs or pre-am's) was it stated that military action was necessary or called for in dealing with this &quot;threat to world peace&quot;.  Granted a theoretical threat is posed by the existence of any weapons, particularly nuclear ones.  If for example, a resolution was passed stating that Britain's nuclear weapons posed a threat to world peace- that is a perfectly true statement in isolation.  I could however Kad, like you did just there, hijack it out of context of the scenario to paint Britain as an imminent threat to world peace that needed to be dealt with by force.  In the context of world affairs &amp; geopolitics, such an argument is patently absurd  That is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the context of the statement with respect to the Iraq situation, nor does it reflect the intent of member-states who voted for it- certainly not in the manner which you've spun it there.  If it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>did</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then I ask you why two superpowers, the United States &amp; UK are unable to convince even a single one of the six undecided nations, two of which are small impoverished African nations.  No amount of arm-twisting or bribing seems to be yielding results- if they truly did perceive Iraq as an imminent threat to world peace in the manner that you describe, surely they'd be queuing up to vote for it!  The fact that so many nations oppose it shows that they neither think military action is called for in 1441, nor justified at the current time.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Not disarming &quot;threatens his grip on power&quot;.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Hardly smawty- and most important of all, he doesn't believe that it does.  Saddam is a surviver first and foremost- with the backing of Arab neighbours and those nations who feel that military action would be precipitate- he has every chance of holding on to power.  Anything that would lose him that support (launching WMD attacks etc) is something that he would never contemplate.  One thing that's interesting to consider is that if the US/UK had taken a more tolerant stance towards inspections and given the process time whilst maintaining forces in the region- that position would force Saddam to comply <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>more</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Currently he can pass off repeated requests to &quot;immediatly disarm&quot; as bullying.  Such a stance increases his grip on power- and it's important to note that despite this, inspections are yielding results.  Remember that 95% of weapons destroyed so far were destroyed through inspections- military action is notoriously unsuccessful in achieving the fundamental goals of disarmament- just look at the action in Yugoslavia for example- disarmament wasn't even on the priority list until late in the conflict- and soldiers are not trained expert inspectors.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why chance it? Especially when 1441 says we don't need to. It's up to Saddam to prove he would not take revenge by disarming<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Why chance it?  Because all the evidence plus the geopolitical situation in the region points to the glaringly obvious- there is no chance being taken in allowing inspections to continue.  Do you seriously believe that putting the lives of so many people, innocent civilian and soldiers alike- do you honestly believe that decision should rest on the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>remote chance</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of a miscalculation by Saddam?  I don't, nor do most people with a grain of sense.  Unless the threat is proven, or is shown to be imminent, then troops should not be committed.  Just as someone shouldn't be arrested simply because(independent of evidence) we &quot;suspect&quot; they're a criminal/terrorist/communist, so should we refuse to commit forces in the absence of a proven and recognised threat.  I put this to you smawty- if all Saddam's neighbours (including <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Israel</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->) do not consider him a serious or imminent threat at this time, then why is force necessary?  Containment is working, deterrence is there as insurance, and inspections are achieving results.  If disarmament is indeed our goal- where's the problem?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why do you think inspections are just now starting to show some success? Could it be that saddam has 310,00 american troops 40,000 UK troops and some aussies on his doorstep? <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If the threat of force is gaining us the results we seek, then where is the need to actually use it Gsam?  Our goal, lest we forget- is disarmament, not regime change.  If enforcing 1441 is indeed our goal, then Iraq's government structure is an irrelevant question- all that matters is disarmament.  Yet regime change has been mentioned time and again- can anyone on this thread point to a single <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>successful</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> regime change in the Middle East in modern history?  And don't even dare say Afghanistan- every report being broadcast from there points to the crumbling of institutions, not the construction of them- promised and non-existent aid seems to be the story of the week <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>every</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> week in the Loya Jirga.<br>
<br>
On a side note- anyone else find it funny that Bush and Blair, both committed Christians with strong fundamental Christian values support a war opposed by every single major Christian denomination?  I find it difficult to reconcile and quite amusing myself- particularly when Dr. Rowan Williams (ArchBishop of Canterbury) deemed unsanctioned military action &quot;morally unsupportable in all good Christian conscience&quot;.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>i fell sorry for blair hes trying to live up to his promises to the US and his own people are gonna cruicfy him for it.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
They certainly will, myself included- you can be sure that if the government go to war without a second UN resolution in this session of the UNSC, I and many others in the UK will <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> vote Labour at the next election.  Without international backing any military action has no legitimacy in my eyes.  Especially not along the ridiculous lines of &quot;a war of aggression fought in self-defence&quot;- I've rarely heard such poppycock out of cabinet ministers from a party I've always supported.  If our forces are committed without a second UN resolution you may be sure that the PM will have to rely on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Tory</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> votes for a majority in favour of military action.  That, plus the resignation of Claire Short, Robin Cook and the Attorney-General who have all promised to resign in the event of unsanctioned military force- I suspect that will spell the beginning of the end for Labour under Tony Blair.  <br>
<br>
Although at one time I would have burned my tongue with these words- I would rather see Charles Kennedy leading this country right now than our current PM.  Foundation hospitals, top-up fees and this precipitate, reckless and completely illogical policy of war in Iraq- all add to an incomprehensible cocktail of measures I utterly abhor.  In the words of Tony Benn:  &quot;If the Prime Minister takes Labour any further to the right, Ian Duncan Smith might well be out of a job far sooner, because of a smiling Tony Blair cutting Conservative policies away from the heart of Labour's core values.&quot;  Perceptive words, and a statement that furthers my convictions about the war policy- it signals a deep split between executive and legislature that has long been brewing, I just pray it won't destroy the function of our democracy before the electorate have a chance to rectify matters.<br>
