<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> If inspectors can't accrue results it'll be because they feel that Saddam is not complying sufficiently for inspections to continue.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hence the root of the problem.  The UN and the anti-Bush (err I mean anti-war) crowd have placed a lot of trust with Saddam.  Trust that he will cooperate, trust that he will be honest, trust that he will not deceive and so and so forth.  While we certainly have seen some cooperation, 10,000 page report, destruction of Al Sammoud 2 missiles, disclosure of UAV research, we have not seen a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>*strategy*</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of cooperation.  On the contrary, I believe <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">we have seen a modicum of cooperation designed to be superficial but nonetheless enough cooperation to keep the anti-Bush (damn anti-war is what I meant) crowd arguing that the inspections are actually working!</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
Listen people, Saddam is trying to deceive you.  Don't let him do it.  What has he down recently that he couldn't have done 4 months ago when this inspection deal began?  What else is he hiding?<br>
<br>
And if he truly is not strategically cooperating, then I still hold, Taranna, that the inspectors job is doomed.  Straight up.  There is no way they can do it without valuable G2 (which I believe they have) and cooperation.<br>
<br>
Make no mistake about it, the UN is fighting for its life here meaning there are strong political forces at work to preserve its life.  If inspections fail, for any reason, even in Taranna's scenarion claiming the US/UK caused the failure by acting multilaterally, it will be a devastating blow to UN legitimacy.  If it can't create a solution that makes everyone happy, what good is it?  It's only good for small, regional, nation level, disputes.<br>
<br>
Don't be duped!<br>
<br>
Yours,<br>
Kad<br>
<br>
PS.  It really is obvious to me, when people say President Bush is a liar, that he is an illegitimate President, that he gained less popular votes than Gore, etc etc ad nauseum, that you are more interested in nailing President Bush more than you are Saddam.  In reality, it's sickening and it's political opportunism at its absoute WORST. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kadandrumtally>Kadandrum Tally</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.cartooncars.com/images/print/bmw/e46m3silv.jpg" BORDER=0> at: 3/15/03 3:03:43 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=smawty>smawty</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#333333>(3/15/03 4:04 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Poll on US Presidents speech is closed</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Hardly smawty- and most important of all, he doesn't believe that it does. Saddam is a surviver first and foremost- with the backing of Arab neighbours and those nations who feel that military action would be precipitate- he has every chance of holding on to power. Anything that would lose him that support (launching WMD attacks etc) is something that he would never contemplate. One thing that's interesting to consider is that if the US/UK had taken a more tolerant stance towards inspections and given the process time whilst maintaining forces in the region- that position would force Saddam to comply more. Currently he can pass off repeated requests to &quot;immediatly disarm&quot; as bullying. Such a stance increases his grip on power- and it's important to note that despite this, inspections are yielding results. Remember that 95% of weapons destroyed so far were destroyed through inspections- military action is notoriously unsuccessful in achieving the fundamental goals of disarmament- just look at the action in Yugoslavia for example- disarmament wasn't even on the priority list until late in the conflict- and soldiers are not trained expert inspectors.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No offense but this is a bunch of poppy-cock.<br>
<br>
Not disarming = Bush+Blair very pissed off = a very serious threat to his grip on power.<br>
And if Saddam truly believes that the U.S. and British military do not threaten his grip on power....well, then that is the most convincing proof of insanity yet.<br>
